<div class="container my-5" style="max-width: 1000px;">

  <h1 class="text-center mb-5">📊 Data Sources & Database Design</h1>

  <!-- DATASET DESCRIPTION -->
  <div class="card mb-4 shadow-sm">
    <div class="card-body">
      <h4 class="mb-3">📊 Dataset Description</h4>

      <p>
        <strong>World Wide Recipe</strong> application uses multiple data sources to build a structured recipe database.
        The primary data source is the <strong>TheMealDB API</strong>, a free public API that provides
        detailed information about meals from various cuisines around the world.
      </p>

      <p>
        The API returns JSON data containing attributes such as meal name, category, cuisine area,
        instructions, image URLs, and ingredients.
      </p>

      <p>
        In addition, the <strong>REST Countries API</strong> is used to enrich the dataset by providing
        geographic information (latitude and longitude) for each cuisine area. This allows the application
        to display recipe origins on a map.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-0">
        The <strong>Faker gem</strong> is also used as a secondary data source to generate tags for recipes,
        adding extra metadata for filtering and organization.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- DATA STRUCTURE -->
  <div class="card mb-4 shadow-sm">
    <div class="card-body">
      <h4 class="mb-3">🧱 Data Structure</h4>

      <p>TheMealDB API organizes data as objects with multiple attributes, including:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>strMeal</strong> - recipe name</li>
        <li><strong>strCategory</strong> - category</li>
        <li><strong>strArea</strong> - cuisine</li>
        <li><strong>strInstructions</strong> - preparation instructions</li>
        <li><strong>strMealThumb</strong> - image URL</li>
        <li><strong>strIngredient1</strong> through <strong>strIngredient20</strong> - ingredients
            <p class="mt-2 text-muted">
                Because ingredients are stored as separate fields in the API response, they are extracted and
                normalized into a separate table in the database.
            </p>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="mt-3"><strong>Database Tables:</strong></p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Recipes</strong> - id, name, instructions, img_url, category_id, area_id</li>
        <li><strong>Categories</strong> - id, name</li>
        <li><strong>Areas</strong> - id, name, latitude, longitude</li>
        <li><strong>Ingredients</strong> - id, name</li>
        <li>
            <strong>Tags</strong> (generated using Faker) - id, name
            <p class="mt-2 text-muted">
                Tags in this application are generated using the Faker gem as an additional data source.
                These tags are randomly assigned to recipes to demonstrate how generated data can be
                integrated into the system. Because they are not derived from API data, they may not always
                accurately reflect the recipe content.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li><strong>RecipeIngredients</strong> - recipe_id, ingredient_id</li>
        <li><strong>RecipeTags</strong> - recipe_id, tag_id</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- DATA INTEGRATION -->
  <div class="card mb-4 shadow-sm">
    <div class="card-body">
      <h4 class="mb-3">🔗 Data Integration</h4>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>TheMealDB API</strong> provides the core data for recipes, categories, areas, and ingredients,
          which are stored in separate tables and linked using foreign keys.
        </li>
        <li>
          Each recipe belongs to a category and an area (<strong>one-to-many relationships</strong>).
        </li>
        <li>
          Ingredients are linked to recipes through a <strong>many-to-many relationship</strong> using the
          <code>recipe_ingredients</code> join table.
        </li>
        <li>
          Tags generated using Faker are connected through a <strong>many-to-many relationship</strong> using
          the <code>recipe_tags</code> join table.
        </li>
        <li>
          The REST Countries API enhances the <strong>areas</strong> table by adding latitude and longitude,
          enabling <strong>map-based visualization</strong>.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- SUMMARY -->
  <div class="card mb-4 shadow-sm">
    <div class="card-body">
      <h4 class="mb-3">🧠 Summary</h4>

      <p class="mb-0">
        By combining structured API data with generated data, this application demonstrates how multiple
        datasets can be integrated into a cohesive system. The relational database design allows efficient
        searching, filtering, and navigation across recipes, categories, ingredients, and regions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ERD -->
  <div class="card shadow-sm">
    <div class="card-body text-center">
      <h4 class="mb-3">🗄️ Entity Relationship Diagram (ERD)</h4>

      <p class="mb-4">
        The diagram below illustrates the database schema and relationships between tables.
      </p>

      <%= image_tag "erd.png", class: "img-fluid rounded shadow", alt: "ERD Diagram" %>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>